Because resources as well as requirements change frequently with IT / development products, I want a feature such as Jira Server has, that the following line can be added to the initiation of the setenv.sh file to allow the server to be reverted to a previous version;
JVM_SUPPORT_RECOMMENDED_ARGS="-Djira.downgrade.allowed=true"

It would be unfortunate if I, or another customer could no longer use their server and its data because of a reduction in compute and/or RAM on the host server, or an increase in server requirements in the future; This would require the time and effort of support staff to resolve, where-as having an option such as above could be well understood and shared with a customer in such a case to allow them to re-install their server with a reduced version to allow for data to be retained until the resources necessary could be managed.

h3. Issue Summary

In cases where Git LFS requests lead to an error, the message contains "\n" characters, which are invalid in the json response (and can cause the client not to show the message)
  
h3. Steps to Reproduce

For an authentication error, as an example, the server returns the following json response:
{code:java}
{"message":"Not authenticated

Please authenticate and try your request again."}
{code}
Note that after "Not authenticated" the message contains two "\n" characters.

 

The git lfs command-line client is unable to parse the message, and instead shows the following:
{code:java}
batch response: Authentication required: Unable to parse HTTP response for POST <URL>: invalid character '\n' in string literal
{code}


h3. Workaround

A workaround, to see the actual error message, is to enable git debug logging (eg GIT_TRACE=1)

This looks to be a recurrence of BSERV-10746 somehow with the introduction of Elasticsearch 6.5.3 on Bitbucket 6.x
h3. Summary

It's not possible to create the Elasticsearch service in Windows – To create the services, one must go over the instructions of the article below, however, it's not possible to create the Elasticsearch service in Windows, since the batch file responsible for creating the service is checking the wrong location.

[https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucketserver/running-bitbucket-server-as-a-windows-service-776640048.html/]
h3. How to Replicate
 # Download the ZIP archive for Bitbucket 6.0/6.1.0
 # Install it.
 # Go over the [Running Bitbucket Server as a Windows service|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucketserver/running-bitbucket-server-as-a-windows-service-776640048.html] to create the services;
 # At step 9 change directory as instructed;
 # At step 10 run the command below to create the Elasticsearch service
{code:java}
service.bat install MyName
{code}

 # This will result in the following message:
{code:java}
C:\Atlassian\Bitbucket\6.1.0\elasticsearch\bin>service.bat install BB6_Search
Installing service      :  "BB6_Search"
Using JAVA_HOME (64-bit):  "C:\Program Files\Java\jre1.8.0_141"
Exception in thread "main" java.nio.file.NoSuchFileException: C:\Atlassian\Bitbucket\6.1.0\elasticsearch\config\jvm.options
{code}

h3. Expected Results

Elasticsearch service should be created
h3. Actual Results

After running the
{code:java}
service.bat install MyName{code}
the following message will be shown and the service won't be created
{noformat}
Exception in thread "main" java.nio.file.NoSuchFileException: C:\Atlassian\Bitbucket\6.1.0\elasticsearch\config\jvm.options
{noformat}
h3. Notes

What is causing the issue is that the {{<Bitbucket Server installation directory>\elasticsearch\bin\elasticsearch-env.bat}} is pointing to the wrong location while trying to find the {{jvm-options}} file.

In the elasticsearch-env.bat file we can see the following
{code:java}
if not defined ES_PATH_CONF (
  set ES_PATH_CONF=!ES_HOME!\config
)
{code}
In the code above we can see that it is trying to check for the file in {{%ES_HOME%\config}} however, there's no {{config}} folder but {{config-template}}.
h3. Workaround
 # Edit the {{<Bitbucket Server installation directory>\elasticsearch\bin\elasticsearch-env.bat}}
 # replace
{code:java}
if not defined ES_PATH_CONF (
  set ES_PATH_CONF=!ES_HOME!\config
)
{code}

 # For
{code:java}
if not defined ES_PATH_CONF (
  set ES_PATH_CONF=!ES_HOME!\config-template
)
{code}

 # run the command in the step 10 of the article again;

When there's a merge conflict, one can click the "More Information" link and get some help on how to fix the conflict. One of the lines is: {{git pull origin the/branch/to/merge/in}}

The implication is that this does a merge. But it may not, depending on the setup. In particular, I've set things up so the default pull action is rebase. Which is generally what's needed when pulling in the latest upstream changes.

May I suggest adding {{--no-rebase}} to that instruction.

h3. Issue Summary
Specific data streams can cause Bitbucket nodes to become unresponsive.

The following can be found in the logs:
{noformat}
WARN  [hz.hazelcast.IO.thread-Acceptor]  c.h.nio.tcp.SocketAcceptorThread [<ip>]:5701 [<cluster name>] [3.7.4-atlassian-43] java.io.UTFDataFormatException: Rejecting request to read 16908289 UTF characters
{noformat}

Leading to this:
{noformat}
2019-02-21 02:22:53,698 WARN  [hz.hazelcast.cached.thread-5]  com.hazelcast.nio.tcp.TcpIpAcceptor [<ip>]:5701 [<cluster name>] [3.11.1] com.atlassian.stash.internal.cluster.NodeConnectionException: Cannot verify whether the nodes connect to the same database and shared home
{noformat}

h3. Workaround
Block any traffic that is not from another Bitbucket node on port 5701 (i.e. set up a firewall).

Track build status to pull request, not just commit id.  The extension of API call would make builds more robust.  If a build fails due to a network or system build issue, not just the build objects, the failure check would be much more useful.

Build status has no way to track a build to a pull request.  A build is tracking to a single git commit.  There should be the ability to track a build status to a pull request and commit id.

From https://developer.atlassian.com/server/bitbucket/how-tos/updating-build-status-for-commits/
{code}
curl -u username:password -H "Content-Type: application/json" -X POST http://localhost:7990/bitbucket/rest/build-status/1.0/commits/9e72f04322c4a1f240e0b3158c67c3c19cdd16e7 -d @build0.json
{code} 

h4. Now:
{code}
{
	"state": "SUCCESSFUL",
	"key": "REPO-MASTER",
	"name": "REPO-MASTER-42",
	"url": "https://bamboo.example.com/browse/REPO-MASTER-42",
	"description": "Changes by John Doe"
}
{code} 

h4. Proposed:
{code}
{
	"state": "SUCCESSFUL",
	"key": "REPO-MASTER",
	"name": "REPO-MASTER-42",
	"url": "https://bamboo.example.com/browse/REPO-MASTER-42",
	"pullrequest": "PR-321"
	"description": "Changes by John Doe"
}
{code} 

Bitbucket would also need to have the kickoff of the build to have the pull request name in the API call that started the build.  This request is due to all of the other Merge Checks are pull request, like reviewers, only modifiers.  With the pull request being attached to a commit only, this can lead to confusion.
